    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking into switching my 9 year old Lab over to a higher protein diet because his vet recommended it for his muscle mass, but i'm a bit confused by the labels. what's a good protein to fat ratio i should be looking for in a senior dog food? i dont want him getting too heavy but i want him to stay strong.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Look for a protein-to-fat ratio that's solid, but don't get too hung up on the exact number, as some food brands are just as good as others as long as the protein is high. A good starting point for a senior dog, especially one needing muscle support, is aiming for something in the range of 25% to 35% protein. This helps build and maintain muscle without overloading him with too much fat, which is a big concern for older dogs. Always check the ingredients list, and if you're still unsure, it's best to check with your vet again.",
